><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> NHS England.</p><p><em> </em></p><p><em> </em></p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><ol><li>Data refers to cases rather than individuals, the same individual may be counted more than once.</li><li>Data for England is for all areas operating to the national service specification.</li><li>Data for London is for two schemes operating to the national service specification, and does not cover the whole of London.</li></ol><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-26T09:57:03.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454238/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454238/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-23","Offenders: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people arrested in (a) England and Wales, (b) London and (c) each London borough were diverted to mental health services after an assessment by liaison and diversion workers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454239","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>There is no intention to change the current policy with regards to identity checks for Secure English Language Testing (SELT). Photocopies, whether certified or not, are not accepted when a candidate sits a test. Only original and valid documents are acceptable. This will allow test centre staff to confirm that the document is genuine and relates to the individual who is sitting the test.</p><p>The only acceptable forms of identification in the UK are:</p><p>• a passport or travel document;</p><p>• a EU Identity Card;</p><p>• a Biometric Residence Permit.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-29T15:54:36.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454239/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454239/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Visas: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to provide certified copies of identity documents to visa applicants to support their applications to undertake an approved English language test.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","28011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454240","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-02T11:01:36.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454240/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454240/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Custodial Treatment: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were imprisoned for non-violent drug offences in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","28001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454241","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Home Office Health and Wellbeing Strategy was launched in February 2015. This sets out three key aims: that every member of staff understands that their health and wellbeing matters; that health and wellbeing is at the centre of change and learning and development programmes and that structural, cultural and demographic factors affecting attendance in the workplace are identified and addressed as appropriate. The strategy is underpinned by a range of modern HR policies and practical advice and services to enhance and promote health and wellbeing such as the employee assistance programme and occupational health services. We also support groups such as ‘Break the Stigma’ and other national mental health campaigns.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-01T17:22:09.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454241/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454241/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Home Office: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's wellness strategy is.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454242","Home Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Code of Conduct for Special Advisers sets out the role of special advisers and describes the range of activities they may undertake. Copies of the Code of Conduct are available in the Libraries of the House and on-line at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468340/CODE_OF_CONDUCT_FOR_SPECIAL_ADVISERS_-_15_OCTOBER_2015_FINAL.pdf</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-02T15:17:32.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454242/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454242/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Home Office: Ministerial Policy Advisors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) policy and (b) other responsibilities are of each special adviser in her Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454243","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>We carefully consider all asylum claims on their individual merits and provide protection for those who need it, in accordance with our international obligations under the Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). This includes an assessment about whether a person who has spoken out against their government is likely to be at risk of persecution or serious harm on return.</p><p>We do not provide any information relating to an asylum claim to the government of a claimant’s country of origin. No one who is at risk of serious harm in their country is expected to return there, but we do expect those who do not need our protection to return home voluntarily.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","27894","2016-03-01T16:35:54.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454243/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454243/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Asylum: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that failed asylum claimants who have spoken out against the government of their country of origin are not deported in such a way as to draw the case to the attention of immigration officials in the destination country.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","27893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454244","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>We carefully consider all asylum claims on their individual merits and provide protection for those who need it, in accordance with our international obligations under the Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). This includes an assessment about whether a person who has spoken out against their government is likely to be at risk of persecution or serious harm on return.</p><p>We do not provide any information relating to an asylum claim to the government of a claimant’s country of origin. No one who is at risk of serious harm in their country is expected to return there, but we do expect those who do not need our protection to return home voluntarily.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","27893","2016-03-01T16:35:55.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454244/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454244/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of her Department's policy of providing information on failed asylum claims to the government of their country of origin on the safety of those claimants on their return to that country.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","27894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454245","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>There are no plans to commission an independent review into visa refusals of applications made by people from the Kurdistan region of Iraq.</p><p>UKVI places great importance of the quality of all entry clearance decisions. All applications are assessed against the Immigration Rules. Decision quality is assured both by local managers and as part of the overall Home Office audit and assurance framework to make sure that the correct decision is reached on all visa applications.</p><p>Further assurance is provided by regular third party inspections and audits.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-29T15:56:35.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454245/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454245/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Visas: Iraq","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2015 to Question 3343, if she will commission an independent review of the reasons for the refusal of visa applications by people from the Kurdistan region of Iraq over the last three years.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","27896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454246","Home Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>The provision and commissioning of police custody healthcare services including custody nurses is the responsibility of individual Police and Crime Commissioners, and healthcare staffing levels are an operational policing matter in conjunction with the custody healthcare service provider. Information on these issues is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","27919","2016-02-26T14:10:19.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454246/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454246/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Metropolitan Police: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the custody nurse vacancy rate was in (a) total and (b) each London borough in the Metropolitan Police area on 1 January of each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454247","Home Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Home Office does not hold data centrally on the number of crimes related to or caused by mental health issues. The Home Office receives data from police forces in England and Wales which show the number of offences recorded. It is not possible to determine which of these were related to or caused by any type of mental health issue.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-26T14:27:38.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454247/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454247/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Crime: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many crimes in (a) England and Wales, (b) London and (c) each London borough were related to or caused by some kind of mental health issue in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454248","Home Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>The provision and commissioning of police custody healthcare services including custody nurses is the responsibility of individual Police and Crime Commissioners, and healthcare staffing levels are an operational policing matter in conjunction with the custody healthcare service provider. Information on these issues is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","27921","2016-02-26T14:10:20.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454248/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454248/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Police Stations: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many recorded incidents there were of no custody nurses being available in police stations when required in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454249","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>Guidance on how queue measurements should be taken at UK border controls was updated in November 2015, following a review. This standardises the approach required for measuring queues. This guidance will be placed in the House Library.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-29T15:52:56.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454249/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454249/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made in standardising the border control queue measurement system across airports, ferry ports and rail terminals.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","27868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454250","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-26","<p>Based on pledges made at Gavi’s replenishment conference in January 2015, the UK share of the total budget for Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, from 2016 to 2020 will be 26%. However, I expect that this level may vary according to other donor pledges.</p><p>Since 2000, Gavi has vaccinated half a billion children and saved 7 million lives. The UK pledge of £1 billion for the 2016 to 2020 period, by itself, is likely to vaccinate an additional 76 million children and save 1.4 million lives.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-26T13:43:29.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454250/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454250/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of donations to the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunisations she expects the UK's share to be at the end of the 2016 to 2020 funding period.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","27856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454251","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-26","<p>We are very concerned about the impact of the current drought on the food security situation for 18 million people across Ethiopia. Britain is working closely with the Government of Ethiopia and the international community to ensure adequate funding for drought response activities.</p><p>We acted quickly and decisively at the onset of the drought by providing emergency food aid for 2.1 million people in 2015. This year, we have committed £40 million to provide food aid to a further 3.8 million people in April.</p><p>In collaboration with the United Nations Children’s Fund, DFID is also ensuring that 120,000 severely malnourished children receive treatment in order to recover quickly.</p><p>Our overall funding for the drought to date is £113 million. We are continuing to work with the Government of Ethiopia and other donors to make sure needs are being met. We are monitoring the situation closely.</p><p>UK Aid resilience work with the Government of Ethiopia has helped prepare 10 million people to cope with this drought.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-26T14:29:24.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454251/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454251/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Ethiopia: Food Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will increase Government funding for emergency food aid to Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","27899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454252","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Code of Conduct for Special Advisers sets out the role of special advisers and describes the range of activities they may undertake. Copies of the Code of Conduct are available in the Libraries of the House and on-line at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468340/CODE_OF_CONDUCT_FOR_SPECIAL_ADVISERS_-_15_OCTOBER_2015_FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468340/CODE_OF_CONDUCT_FOR_SPECIAL_ADVISERS_-_15_OCTOBER_2015_FINAL.pdf</a></p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-29T17:21:48.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454252/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454252/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Department for International Development: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the (a) policy and (b) other responsibilities are of each special adviser in her Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454253","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>DFID seeks to create a workplace where we protect the health, safety and wellbeing of staff, optimise the opportunity to promote a healthy workforce, maintain safe systems of work and proactively support the physical and emotional wellbeing of staff.​ These principles are reflected throughout DFIDs HR Policies and approach to People Management.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-01T17:54:19.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454253/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454253/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Department for International Development: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her Department's wellness strategy is.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454254","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>DFID works closely with the FCO to assess and monitor the civil and political rights context in the countries where it has programmes. DFID draws on the FCO’s annual Human Rights and Democracy Report, which takes international human rights obligations as its starting point, and assesses FCO country specific updates to that report. It takes into account the views of a range of sources including EU and other development partners, and civil society reports.</p><p>DFID provides aid to governments when it is satisfied that they share Britain’s commitments to reducing poverty and to respecting human rights. Before providing aid to a partner government, DFID assesses their commitment to four Partnership Principles. These include a commitment to poverty reduction; respecting human rights and other international obligations; improving public financial management, promoting good governance and transparency, and fighting corruption; and strengthening domestic accountability.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-01T17:09:24.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454254/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454254/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Developing Countries: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what metrics she uses in monitoring human rights abuse (a) by governments and (b) in countries in receipt of UK aid.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","27995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454255","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>Between 2013 and 2015 DFID provided UNICEF in Eritrea with £10 million for child and maternal health and the provision of clean water and sanitation.</p><p>In December 2015 DFID provided a further £3 million for nutrition support activities and water and sanitation in areas affected by El Nino in the Horn of Africa through UNICEF’s regional programme, which covers Eritrea.</p><p>Over the past 2 years funding to support primarily Eritrean refugees in Ethiopia totalled £1.6 million and focussed on child protection and related work on anti-smuggling and trafficking.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T15:01:28.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454255/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454255/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Eritrea: EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made representations to the EU on its funding of aid and development projects in Eritrea.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","27978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454256","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>I will publish further details of the Global Challenges Research Fund alongside allocation of the Science Budget shortly.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-02T11:03:41.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454256/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454256/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-23","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish details of the Global Challenges research fund announced in the Government strategy paper, UK aid: tackling global challenges in the national interest, published on 23 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","28035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454257","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>As a member of the European Development Fund Committee (EDF) my Department scrutinises all EDF programming. The National Indicative Programme (NIP) for Eritrea under EDF 11 was considered at the Committee on the 17<sup>th</sup> of November 2015 and received a positive opinion. Prior to that DFID officials worked with other member states to secure a joint EU and member state approach to linking implementation of the NIP with successful dialogue on human rights.</p><p>We continue to monitor this, both in country and in Brussels, alongside other member states.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T15:01:04.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454257/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454257/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Eritrea: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding her Department has allocated to projects which are primarily aimed at Eritrean nationals in the last three years; and in which countries such projects are based.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","28092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454258","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The UK is working closely with the French Government on all aspects of the migrant situation in Calais; however the management of the migrant camps in France is the responsibility of the French Government. They have recently increased capacity in heated container accommodation for vulnerable groups in the Calais camp, where women, children and the sick and injured are given priority.</p><p>Both the UK and France are clear that the right course of action is to move migrants away from Calais and for genuine refugees to be offered protection within the French asylum system. That is why as part of the UK-France Joint Declaration of 20 August 2015, the UK has provided £3.6million (or €5 million) per year for two years to help provide support and facilities for migrants at centres elsewhere in France.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:34:14.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454258/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454258/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-23","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on children whose refugee shelters in Calais are due to be demolished by the French government.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","28108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454259","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-26","<p>It is for individual government departments to determine the legal basis of their ODA spend.</p><p>DFID does not monitor what proportion of other government departments’ Official Development Assistance spending was subject to IDA 2002.</p><p>Details of departmental spend on Official Development Assistance (ODA) can be found in the National Statistics publication Statistics on International Development (SID) at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development/about/statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-international-development/about/statistics</a>, although this does not identify the proportions of spend under IDA 2002.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-26T14:30:48.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454259/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454259/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which Departments other than her Department, the Ministry of Defence, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Department for Energy and Climate Change have responsibility for Overseas Development Assistance (ODA) spending under the terms of the International Development Act 2002; and what proportion of those Departments' ODA spending was subject to the Act in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454260","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-01","<p>DFID no longer has a bilateral poverty reduction programme in Indonesia. However, as part of UK Government action to mitigate against climate change, we work in partnership with the Indonesian national and provincial governments to help secure community access to forest land in Papua to promote a sustainable green economy, whilst supporting local livelihoods.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-03-01T17:09:37.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454260/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454260/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Papua: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the effect on poverty reduction in West Papua, Indonesia, of the reported ban on non-governmental organisations working in that area.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","28156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454261","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-26","<p>DFID would not record or have access to details of former employees who have been rehired by other government departments.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-26T14:24:25.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454261/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454261/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-23","Department for International Development: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff leaving employment at her Department in the last three years have subsequently been rehired within 12 months by the (a) Foreign and Commonwealth Office, (b) Ministry of Defence, (c) Department for Energy and Climate Change, (d) Department for Culture, Media and Sport, (e) Cabinet Office and (f) HM Treasury.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","28141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454262","Ministry of Justice","true","2016-04-06","<p>As the Justice Secretary has said, the safety and welfare of all those in custody is vital.</p><p>Although youth crime is down, reoffending rates are far too high and the care and supervision of young people in custody is not good enough. Restraint should only be used as a last resort, when young people are putting their own safety and the safety of others at risk.</p><p>In 2012, we introduced the Minimising and Managing Physical Restraint (MMPR). Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Prisons has welcomed the significant improvements that MMPR has brought.</p><p>The number of minor and serious injuries requiring medical treatment resulting from RPIs is published in Chapter 8 of the Youth Justice Annual Statistics:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/youth-justice-annual-statistics-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/youth-justice-annual-statistics-2014-to-2015</a></p><p>We are investigating the accuracy of all restraint injury data from Medway Secure Training Centre.</p><p>The number of young people that establishments recorded as injured during incidents that required Restrictive Physical Intervention in each institution in the youth secure estate in each of the last eight years is set out in the attached document. This includes the following categories of injury: (i) serious injury requiring hospital treatment (ii) minor injuries requiring medical treatment and (iii) minor injuries, no treatment required.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-06T14:44:19.67Z","2016-04-08T09:51:59.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454262/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454262/answer","Number of injuries sustained by children during restraint.xls","Number of injuries sustained by children during restraint.xls","injuries sustained by children during restraint","injuries sustained by children during restraint","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454262/answer","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454262/answer/previousversion/54110","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454262/answer/previousversion/54110",,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Youth Custody: Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many injuries were sustained by children during restraint in each custodial institution in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454263","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-18","<p>Violence in prisons has increased in recent years. The nature of offenders currently in custody and the widespread availability of new psychoactive substances have both contributed to making prisons less safe. There is no single, simple solution to the problems we face but we are making progress.</p><p>We have launched a two year Violence Reduction project to help us to gain a better understanding of the causes and characteristics of violence. We are also trialling the use of body worn cameras in prisons, training sniffer dogs to detect new psychoactive substances and have made it an offence to smuggle new psychoactive substances into prison. However, ultimately the only way to reduce violence in our prisons is to give governors and those who work in prisons the tools necessary to more effectively reform and rehabilitate offenders.</p><p>Many Concerted indiscipline incidents vary widely in nature and duration and many of these incidents are relatively minor and of short duration and cause little disruption to the prison regime.</p><p>Note: The figures included in the table attached, have been drawn from the NOMS Incident Reporting System. Care is taken when processing and analysing the returns but the detail collected is subject to the inaccuracies inherent in any large scale recording system. Although the figures are shown to the last case the figures may not be accurate to that level.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-18T11:49:15.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454263/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454263/answer","28151 Concerted Indiscipline Incidents in Prison 2005-16.xlsx","28151 Concerted Indiscipline Incidents in Prison 2005-16.xlsx","Concerted Indiscipline Incidents 2005-16","Concerted Indiscipline Incidents 2005-16","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454263/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Prisons: Discipline","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many concerted indiscipline incidents of each type have occurred in each prison establishment in each month since May 2005.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454264","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-06","<p>Violence in prisons has increased in recent years. These figures demonstrate that the Prime Minister and the Justice Secretary are right and out prisons badly need reform.</p><p> </p><p>We are already trialling the use of body worn cameras in prisons, training sniffer dogs to detect new psychoactive substances and have made it an offence to smuggle new psychoactive substances into prison. However, ultimately the only way to reduce violence in our prisons is to give governors and those who work in prisons the tools necessary to more effectively rehabilitate offenders.</p><p> </p><p>Hostage incidents are rare occurrences. The table attached provides details of hostage incidents, broken down by establishment and victim type.</p><p> </p><p>Note: These figures have been drawn from the NOMS Incident Reporting System. Care is taken when processing and analysing the returns but the detail collected is subject to the inaccuracies inherent in any large scale recording system. Although the figures are shown to the last case the figures may not be accurate to that level.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-06T15:25:57.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454264/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454264/answer","28152 - table.xlsx","28152 - table.xlsx","Hostage incidents in Prison - 2010 - 2016","Hostage incidents in Prison - 2010 - 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454264/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Prisons: Hostage Taking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many hostage incidents in which a (a) prison officer and (b) prisoner was taken hostage have taken place in each prison establishment since January 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454265","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-26","<p>The number of responses received on the proposal to close Hammersmith County Court (formally West London County Court) were (a) two in favour and (b) 14 against.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation response is available online at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/moj" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/moj</a>.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-26T14:29:45.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454265/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454265/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","County Courts: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many responses to his Department's consultation on the closure of Hammersmith Court were (a) in favour of and (b) against the closure.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454266","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-26","<p>HMP&amp;YOI Feltham is a split site which holds both young people (under 18’s) and young adults (18-20 year olds). The two cohorts are managed distinctly and there are separate education contracts and different providers for each.</p><p> </p><p>The Youth Justice Board oversees the management of the education contract for young people at Feltham. Prior to August 2015, education providers were only required to deliver 15 hours of education. In August 2015, we increased the requirement for education providers in public sector Young Offender Institutions (YOIs) to 27 hours of education a week, which is supplemented by 3 hours of physical exercise.</p><p> </p><p>Whist the majority of education time is protected, it is expected that young people will miss some lessons to attend appointments such as court appearances, medical appointments and legal visits.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides the average number of classroom based education hours, alternative activities hours and physical education hours per week accessed by young people at Feltham YOI since 16 August 2015.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Education</p></td><td><p>Average hours per week</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Classroom based learning</p></td><td><p>13.99</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Alternative activities(1)</p></td><td><p>7.72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Physical education(2)</p></td><td><p>1.43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>23.15</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(1) Alternative activities include interventions relating to offending behaviour, focus groups, Release on Temporary licence etc.</p><p>(2) Data is from 9 October only.</p><p>This table does not include outreach education provision which is provided to young people who are not able to engage with class room based education.</p><p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) and the Youth Justice Board are working with education providers to address delivery challenges and increase the number of education hours received by young people.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-26T14:41:59.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454266/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454266/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Feltham Young Offender Institution: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average amount of time is a prisoner spends on education or work-related activities at Feltham Young Offenders Institution.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454267","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the reply given to my hon. Friend the Member for York Outer on 15 June 2015, which can be found at <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-08/1400/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-08/1400/</a>.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-02T10:55:15.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454267/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454267/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Missing Persons: Guardianship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if the Government will bring forward proposals for legislation to establish guardianship provisions to assist families in managing the affairs of missing persons.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","28047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454268","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-03-02T15:54:49.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454268/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454268/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Pathology: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many pathologists qualified to conduct post-mortems there were in (a) 2010 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","28044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454269","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Ministry of Justices (MoJ) Wellbeing strategy seeks to help foster a culture that promotes physical and mental wellbeing for all staff and to make the management of health and wellbeing part of our daily routine.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-02T10:46:10.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454269/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454269/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Ministry of Justice: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his Department's wellness strategy is.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454270","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Code of Conduct for Special Advisers sets out the role of special advisers and describes the range of activities they may undertake. Copies of the Code of Conduct are available in the Library of the House and online at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468340/CODE_OF_CONDUCT_FOR_SPECIAL_ADVISERS_-_15_OCTOBER_2015_FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/468340/CODE_OF_CONDUCT_FOR_SPECIAL_ADVISERS_-_15_OCTOBER_2015_FINAL.pdf</a></p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-01T16:36:02.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454270/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454270/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Ministry of Justice: Ministerial Policy Advisors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the (a) policy and (b) other responsibilities are of each special adviser in his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","27957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454271","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-03","<p>The average time taken for CICA to reach an initial decision in the years 2013-14 and 2014-15 were as follows. Note that this time includes cases where no compensation was payable within the terms of the Scheme. Comparable data going back to financial year 2010-11 is included.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p>7.2 months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p>7.8 months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p>8.8 months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>10.4 months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>10.9 months</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The average time taken for CICA to reach an initial decision where compensation was offered, during the years 2013-14 and 2014-15 were as follows. Comparable data for the average time taken to make a decision where a monetary award was offered is not held.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>14 months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>16 months</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In the last year, CICA have focused on clearing the older cases from its caseload, which has allowed CICA to reduce the proportion of cases which are more than two years old. However, this has contributed to longer average clearance times.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-03T13:59:09.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454271/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454271/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Criminal Injuries Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time between application to initial decision was for awards issued by the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Graham Stuart","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","27970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454272","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-02","<p>NOMS defend robustly all claims brought and successfully defend two thirds of claims brought by prisoners. It is not possible accurately to separate prisoner compensation claims against prison staff from other similar claims (e.g. assaults by other prisoners).</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-02T10:50:52.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454272/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454272/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-23","Prisoners: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many compensation claims against prison staff were made by prisoners in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","27892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454273","Department of Health","false","2016-02-26","<p>Due to small numbers involved and risk of deductive disclosure, the number of cases of Legionella pneumonia in people in prisons in England cannot be provided.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-26T09:58:05.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454273/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454273/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-23","Prisons: Legionnaires' Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many Legionnaires' disease incidents have been reported in each prison since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","27914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454274","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-26","<p>Tool or implement losses are infrequent occurrences, however each one is taken seriously and subject to local investigation. The number of losses has remained stable over the last 10 years.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides a breakdown of the number of tool or implement losses reported between May 2010 and January 2016.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="7"><p><strong>Tool/Implement loss incidents in prisons<sup>1</sup>, England and Wales, 2006 to 2015</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2006</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of incidents</p></td><td><p>284</p></td><td><p>291</p></td><td><p>282</p></td><td><p>257</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>313</p></td><td><p>261</p></td><td><p>311</p></td><td><p>295</p></td><td><p>315</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p>(1) Includes NOMS operated Immigration Removal Centres</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>