34/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-22","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many assessments for disabled students' allowance (DSA) were carried out by an independent needs assessor in each year since 2009-10; what the average such award was in each of those years; and who was contracted to carry out each of those assessments in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453635","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>There are 41 civil servants in my Department primarily working on trade policy. Of these 10 are primarily working on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership. The Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement was one of a number of trade negotiations being handled by a team of 5 BIS officials. They are assisted by officials in other Government Departments, notably the Department for International Development and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, as well as by other officials within my Department for whom trade policy is not their primary responsibility.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T16:28:57.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453635/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453635/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-22","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many officials of his Department are (a) responsible for external trade policy, (b) working on policy related to the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership and (c) worked on policy related to the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","27658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453636","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-01","<p>Students wishing to apply for Disabled Students’ Allowances (DSAs) need to provide evidence of their disability to Student Finance England (SFE) in order to demonstrate their eligibility. Depending on their disability, this needs to come from a medical doctor or other suitably qualified professional. Information about whether this evidence is provided by someone connected to the students’ HE provider is not held centrally.</p><p>Students are encouraged to speak to their institution’s disability adviser, to ensure they are receiving all the help that is available to them. However, students do not need to disclose their disability to their HE provider in order to apply for DSAs.</p><p>All disabled higher education students who are eligible for Disabled Students’ Allowances are referred to an independent assessment centre so as to identify the type and level of support they require.</p><p>Students are free to choose which assessment centre they wish to attend. They can find a centre via the DSAs Quality Assurance Group’s website:</p><p><a href="http://www.dsa-qag.org.uk/students/find-an-assessment-centre" target="_blank">http://www.dsa-qag.org.uk/students/find-an-assessment-centre</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-01T16:26:57.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453636/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453636/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-22","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of applicants for disabled students' allowance (DSA) used supporting notes from (a) medical professionals connected to and (b) medical professionals not connected to their higher education institution to back up their application; and what estimate he has made of the proportion of people who claim DSA without the knowledge of their higher education institution.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453637","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-25T14:48:31.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453637/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453637/answer","27634  .pdf","27634  .pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - National Minimum Wage Rate","UKSA Letter to Member - National Minimum Wage Rate","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453637/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-22","Average Earnings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in employment earn (a) the national minimum wage rate which will apply from 1 April 2016 and (b) between that rate and one per cent above that rate.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","27643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453638","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>Departments publish details of Ministers meetings' with external organisations routinely on www.Gov.uk.</p><p>Details of meetings held during the period October – December 2015 will be published in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-26T14:00:09.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453638/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453638/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-22","Cabinet Office: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with (i) arms manufacturers, (ii) tobacco manufacturers and (iii) representatives of the Israeli embassy since the period covered in his Department's most recent ministerial gifts, hospitality, travel and meetings data release.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","27634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453639","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>As was the case under previous administrations details of internal discussions are not normally disclosed.</p><p>The UK Statistics Authority’s strategy, <em>Better</em> <em>Statistics Better Decisions</em>, recognises the need for statistics to keep pace with a fast-changing world, including in the context of an increased emphasis on the devolution of decision-making powers to the nations, regions and cities of the UK.</p><p>A list of regional statistics which the UK is required to provide under European Regulations, including the level of breakdown, is available online at <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/140934/4381644/Regional_statistics_overview.xls" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/140934/4381644/Regional_statistics_overview.xls</a>.</p><p>While the Regulations require that any data used to produce these statistics be of sufficient quality, the regulations do not specify how data is obtained; this is a matter left to Member States to decide. Beyond those statistics included on this list, official statistics are broken down at different geographies, depending on needs and available data.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","27736","2016-02-25T16:37:48.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453639/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453639/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-22","Combined Authorities: Statistics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions he has had with the Office for National Statistics on devolving statistics and data collecting powers and obligations when powers are devolved to combined authorities.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","27733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453640","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>As was the case under previous administrations details of internal discussions are not normally disclosed.</p><p>The UK Statistics Authority’s strategy, <em>Better</em> <em>Statistics Better Decisions</em>, recognises the need for statistics to keep pace with a fast-changing world, including in the context of an increased emphasis on the devolution of decision-making powers to the nations, regions and cities of the UK.</p><p>A list of regional statistics which the UK is required to provide under European Regulations, including the level of breakdown, is available online at <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/140934/4381644/Regional_statistics_overview.xls" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/140934/4381644/Regional_statistics_overview.xls</a>.</p><p>While the Regulations require that any data used to produce these statistics be of sufficient quality, the regulations do not specify how data is obtained; this is a matter left to Member States to decide. Beyond those statistics included on this list, official statistics are broken down at different geographies, depending on needs and available data.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","27733","2016-02-25T16:37:48.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453640/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453640/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-22","Government: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what requirements are in place for (a) the Office for National Statistics (ONS) and (b) other government agencies to collect data on a regional basis; and what discussions he has had with the ONS to collect the provision of regional data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","27736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453641","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Department for Transport compensated Transport for London (TfL) in full for the projected impact on their revenues of the Chancellor of the Exchequer’s September 2014 announcement on regulated rail fares. The Department did this by paying TfL an additional £43 million, spread over two financial years (£7m in 2014/15, and £36m in 2015/16), by means of a variation to their core grant (the GLA transport grant, paid under section 101 of the Greater London Authority Act 1999). This followed consultation with HM Treasury and with the Greater London Authority.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-25T16:25:23.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453641/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453641/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-22","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 28 November 2014 to Question 215333, what amount was paid to Transport for London in relation to the decision to raise Transport for London rail fares by the retail price index in January 2015.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","27763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453642","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is unable to provide any information which would identify its customers. The Commissioners for Revenue and Customs Act 2005 gives HMRC a duty of confidentiality which applies to all information it holds in connection with its functions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2014-15 HMRC issued 677 penalties to the total value of £768,000. This is for all HMRC supervised businesses in the UK. The total includes estate agency businesses which HMRC supervised from 1 April 2014. This is three times the total value of penalties issued in 2013-14.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T16:27:52.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453642/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453642/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Money Laundering: Estate Agents","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which estate agents in London have been penalised for failing to comply with the Money Laundering Regulations 2007 in each year since the introduction of those regulations; and what the level of the fine was in each such case.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453643","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is unable to provide any information which would identify its customers. The Commissioners for Revenue and Customs Act 2005 gives HMRC a duty of confidentiality which applies to all information it holds in connection with its functions.</p><p>In 2014-15 HMRC issued 677 penalties to the total value of £768,000. This is for all HMRC supervised businesses in the UK. The total includes estate agency businesses which HMRC supervised from 1 April 2014. This is three times the total value of penalties issued in 2013-14.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-05-04T15:46:55.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453643/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453643/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Money Laundering: Estate Agents","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many estate agents in (a) England and Wales and (b) London have been penalised for failing to comply with the Money Laundering Regulations 2007.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453644","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>At Autumn Statement 2015, the Government announced a consultation on aspects of the Transaction in Securities rules, and published draft legislation shortly afterwards. A tax information and impact note setting out expected impacts was published on 9<sup>th</sup> December, and can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/corporation-tax-income-tax-and-capital-gains-tax-company-distributions.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-01T15:25:22.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453644/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453644/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on stakeholders of the proposed changes to the Transactions in Securities rules.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","27686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453645","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government announced at Autumn Statement 2015 that it will consider bringing forward legislation to amend the changes made by Finance Act 2015 to entrepreneurs’ relief, in order to support businesses by ensuring that the relief is available on certain genuine commercial transactions. Changes to taxation are announced by the Chancellor at the Budget and the effect of changes are published in a Tax Information and Impact Note.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-01T15:36:57.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453645/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453645/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Small Businesses: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on stakeholders of the proposed changes to entrepreneurial tax relief.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","27687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453646","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government is working to help all construction companies to expand and create jobs. At the Spending Review the housing budget was doubled to over £2 billion per year, and the Chancellor also committed to £100 billion of spending in this Parliament for new roads, rail, flood defences and other vital projects.</p><p>We are making sure that small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) have access to government contract opportunities, making it easier for them to do business with us. We are requiring departments to publish details of future projects on the “contracts finder” website, giving businesses the confidence and time to invest in relevant skills, labour and capabilities.</p><p>Access to finance can be a barrier to growth. There is a range of support and assistance available through the Business Support Helpline. The British Business Bank is a government-owned business development bank dedicated to making finance markets work better for smaller businesses, through schemes such as the Enterprise Finance Guarantee (EFG). The British Business Bank promotes the EFG to high street lenders to encourage them to lend to viable smaller businesses that would otherwise be declined for lacking adequate security.</p><p>More widely the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills’ red tape challenge programmes are targeting rules and regulations in the construction sector. Many of those red tape requirements fall disproportionately heavily on smaller construction employers.</p><p>In addition the Government is placing employers, including small businesses, in the lead in developing new apprenticeship standards and providing financial support. Specific grants are available for smaller businesses and for younger apprentices. In addition there is a range of support for all approved learning outcomes available from the Construction Industry Training Board.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-01T16:59:50.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453646/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453646/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-22","Construction: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what work his Department is undertaking to assist small and medium-sized enterprises in the construction industry to expand and create more jobs.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","27688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453647","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government has asked the Low Pay Commission to increase the National Living Wage to 60% of median earnings by 2020. This is a level consistent with the recommendations of leading experts in the Bain Report. Our target is for the National Living Wage to reach £9 by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>On this basis, we have set the initial rate at £7.20 from April 2016. This marks the first step towards our target and represents a £900 a year increase in earnings for a full-time worker on the National Minimum Wage.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T16:21:16.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453647/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453647/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what formula was used to calculate the Government's proposed living wage.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","27715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453648","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Welfare Reform and Work Bill introduces a four-year freeze for the main rates of most working-age benefits from 2016-17 to 2019-20, as part of the Government’s welfare reforms that are moving the country to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society.</p><p> </p><p>The freeze does not apply to benefits related to the additional costs of disability, such as Disability Living Allowance and Personal Independence Payment; to the support group component of Employment and Support Allowance or the limited capability for work and work-related activity amount in Universal Credit; or to the disability premiums in Jobseeker’s Allowance, Employment and Support Allowance, Income Support or Housing Benefit. Carers benefits and premiums are also exempted from the freeze.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-01T16:19:45.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453648/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453648/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-22","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether benefits for people with disabilities will be exempt from the freeze on working-age benefits.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453649","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>The information requested for points (a), (b) and (c) is not available. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not have a central register of all internal and external meetings. Moreover, the details of gifts and hospitality is not broken down by grade.</p><p> </p><p>On point (d), HMRC officials at Grade 7 and above undertook 1,557 overseas journeys by air or rail to 88 different destinations in 2014-15, and 709 journeys to 65 destinations in the first half of 2015-16.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-25T15:26:06.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453649/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453649/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) meetings, (b) hospitality, (c) gifts and (d) overseas travel officials at Grade 7 or above in HM Revenue and Customs have received or undertaken in (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","27823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453650","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>This level of detail is not collected on VAT or any other tax return.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-01T15:32:39.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453650/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453650/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Food: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what revenue was received by the Exchequer from the total amount of food imported by the UK from other member states of the EU in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","27726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453651","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The government has published “Fixing the foundations: Creating a more prosperous nation”, its plan for productivity growth in the UK. This plan outlines the steps the government is taking to encourage further investment in the drivers of productivity growth, including science, education, skills and infrastructure. It also sets out the ways the government is promoting a dynamic economy through reforming planning laws, boosting competition and creating a Northern Powerhouse.</p><p> </p><p>These steps include: investing £6.9 billion in the UK’s research infrastructure up to 2021; introducing a levy on large employers to help deliver 3 million apprenticeships starts this Parliament; guaranteeing that all revenue raised from VED in England from 2020-21 will be allocated to a new Roads Fund and invested directly back into the strategic road network; and creating a new “zonal” system which will grant automatic permission in principle on brownfield sites.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-29T16:18:27.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453651/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453651/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce the productivity gap.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","27727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453652","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>The recent performance of the labour market speaks for itself, the unemployment rate is at a 10 year low and the employment rate is the highest since records began. Over the last year nearly 3 out of 4 jobs created have been full time jobs. Through Universal Credit and the National Living Wage we are ensuring it always pays to increase your hours, and our childcare offer of 30 hours means more families are able to do so.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-25T17:27:16.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453652/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453652/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of people who want to work full-time who are in part-time rather than full-time work.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","27835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453653","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>This level of detail is not requested on VAT returns and therefore data is not available on how much VAT was raised on domestic energy in each of the last five years.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-25T15:29:56.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453653/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453653/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Energy: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an estimate of the revenue the Government received from VAT on domestic energy in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","27805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453654","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>This level of detail is not requested on VAT returns and therefore data is not available on how much VAT was raised on hotel stays and restaurant meals in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-25T15:28:03.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453654/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453654/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an estimate of the revenue the Government received from VAT on hotel stays and restaurant meals in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","27806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453655","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Departments publish details of Ministers meetings' with external organisations routinely on Gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>Details of meetings held during the period October – December 2015 will be published in due course.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T16:43:43.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453655/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453655/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Treasury: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with (i) arms manufacturers, (ii) tobacco manufacturers and (iii) representatives of the Israeli embassy since the period covered in the Cabinet Office's most recent ministerial gifts, hospitality, travel and meetings data release.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","27640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453657","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Autumn Statement announced that the Government will legislate to remove the need for a referendum to introduce Welsh Rates of Income Tax. The Government has been clear that it will amend the draft Wales Bill to do this.</p><p> </p><p>The programme of fiscal reform has been designed for a purpose: to empower the Welsh Government with further tools and levers to deliver more growth and be more accountable to the people of Wales by raising more of the money they spend.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to discuss the implementation of Welsh Rates of Income Tax – including the financial arrangements - with a range of interested stakeholders, including the Welsh Government.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","27627 ; 27664","2016-03-01T16:20:44.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453657/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453657/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Income Tax: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of what the most appropriate fiscal framework mechanism would be to accompany the devolution of income tax powers of Wales.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","27626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453658","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Autumn Statement announced that the Government will legislate to remove the need for a referendum to introduce Welsh Rates of Income Tax. The Government has been clear that it will amend the draft Wales Bill to do this.</p><p> </p><p>The programme of fiscal reform has been designed for a purpose: to empower the Welsh Government with further tools and levers to deliver more growth and be more accountable to the people of Wales by raising more of the money they spend.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to discuss the implementation of Welsh Rates of Income Tax – including the financial arrangements - with a range of interested stakeholders, including the Welsh Government.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","27626 ; 27664","2016-03-01T16:20:44.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453658/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453658/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Income Tax: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the fiscal framework to accompany the devolution of income tax powers to Wales.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","27627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453659","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>HM Treasury and HM Revenue and Customs officials receive representations from, and undertake discussions on an ongoing basis with a variety of stakeholders, including companies, representative bodies, other government departments and NGOs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>These representations and discussions inform the programme of tax treaty negotiations that are approved by Ministers and published at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/double-taxation-agreements-developments-and-planned-negotiations.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-25T15:21:20.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453659/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453659/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Double Taxation: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) discussions he has had with and (b) representations he has received from (i) businesses, (ii) members of the public and (iii) other stakeholders on new double taxation treaties since 2010.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","27657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453660","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>HM Treasury has not carried out any assessment of the overall economic impact of gaming machines. The Gambling Commission regularly publishes a range of statistics relating to the gambling industry<strong>.</strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-03-01T17:48:32.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453660/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453660/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the economic impact of fixed odds betting terminals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453661","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Autumn Statement announced that the Government will legislate to remove the need for a referendum to introduce Welsh Rates of Income Tax. The Government has been clear that it will amend the draft Wales Bill to do this.</p><p> </p><p>The programme of fiscal reform has been designed for a purpose: to empower the Welsh Government with further tools and levers to deliver more growth and be more accountable to the people of Wales by raising more of the money they spend.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to discuss the implementation of Welsh Rates of Income Tax – including the financial arrangements - with a range of interested stakeholders, including the Welsh Government.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","27626 ; 27627","2016-03-01T16:20:44.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453661/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453661/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Income Tax: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the specific deduction method to accompany the devolution of income tax powers to Wales.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","27664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453662","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) produce the forecast for public sector net debt. Based on the OBR’s November 2015 ‘Economic and fiscal outlook’, public sector net debt is expected to fall as a share of GDP in every year of the forecast period.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-25T15:23:19.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453662/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453662/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Public Sector Debt","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether public sector net debt is forecast to fall in the next financial year.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","27604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453663","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-01T15:29:07.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453663/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453663/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many tax credit claims have been (a) identified as potentially fraudulent and (b) reviewed by Concentrix in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","27602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453664","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The changes to tax relief for travel and subsistence only affect those who work through an employment intermediary. The Government’s assessment of the effects of the measure can be found in the Tax Information and Impact Note:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-employment-intermediaries-and-relief-for-travel-and-subsistence/income-tax-employment-intermediaries-and-relief-for-travel-and-subsistence" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-employment-intermediaries-and-relief-for-travel-and-subsistence/income-tax-employment-intermediaries-and-relief-for-travel-and-subsistence</a></p><p> </p><p>Further assessment can be found in the summary of responses to the consultation document published on this change: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/483389/Employment_Intermediaries_and_Tax_Relief_for_Travel_and_Subsistence_-_Summary_of_Responses__M7057_.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/483389/Employment_Intermediaries_and_Tax_Relief_for_Travel_and_Subsistence_-_Summary_of_Responses__M7057_.pdf</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-01T15:35:18.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453664/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453664/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Self-employed: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on levels of self-employment in the construction industry of his proposed changes to tax relief for travel and subsistence.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","27586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453665","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>In June 2015, the fourth EU Anti-Money Laundering Directive (‘the Directive) was formally adopted. Member States have up until June 2017 to transpose the Directives requirements, into national law.</p><p> </p><p>With regards to the Government’s plans to consult on the transposition of the Directive, it intends to do so by early spring, with consultation running for a full 12 weeks. The consultation will cover areas where the Directive has given us options or direction on how we transpose its provisions, as well as areas where we can improve the UK’s anti-money laundering and counter financing of terrorism (AML/CFT) regime.</p><p> </p><p>By undertaking this work, we are further ensuring that our anti-money laundering and counter-financing of terrorism regime is robust and sufficiently responsive to emerging threats.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-25T17:38:20.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453665/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453665/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Money Laundering: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to consult on the transposition of the fourth anti-money-laundering directive.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453666","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government believes that the key to improving affordability in domestic rents is to increase the supply of homes. That is why the Government has taken measures to attract billions of pounds of investment to build homes specifically for private rent. This includes a £3.5 billion debt guarantee scheme to support the delivery of new homes purpose built for private rent.</p><p> </p><p>At the Spending Review the Government set out its Five Point Plan for increasing housing supply. This includes plans to deliver 400,000 affordable home starts by 2020/21, including 10,000 Rent to Buy homes; a £2billion fund to provide infrastructure on large housing sites; a £1billion fund to provide loans to SME builders; further reforms to the planning system and the release of public sector land for 160,000 homes.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-01T11:22:47.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453666/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453666/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Rents: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he plans to take to reduce domestic rent prices in London.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","27839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453667","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Treasury has commissioned no external research on the productivity gap. The Treasury’s analysis is laid out in Annex A of the Productivity Plan, which was published in July 2015 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443898/Productivity_Plan_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443898/Productivity_Plan_web.pdf</a>, pages 77-82). This draws on evidence from academics, the Bank of England and others.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-25T17:15:27.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453667/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453667/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what research his Department has (a) commissioned and (b) carried out on the structural factors in the economy that have contributed to the scale of the productivity gap.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","27800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453668","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>The government set out its understanding on the reasons for the productivity gap in Annex A of the Productivity Plan, published in July 2015 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443898/Productivity_Plan_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443898/Productivity_Plan_web.pdf</a>, pages 77-82).</p><p> </p><p>A number of factors contribute to the UK’s lower level of productivity compared to the most productive countries in the world, including lower levels of investment, especially in research and development. There are a further set of explanations for the shortfall in performance post-crisis, including impaired resource allocation in the economy, the disproportionate impacts on some high productivity sectors, substitution of labour for capital, labour hoarding in the initial phase of the recession and measurement issues.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-25T17:13:24.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453668/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453668/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons for the scale of the productivity gap.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","27801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453669","Home Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>Fire safety in care homes is the responsibility of the operator who is required under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 to assess the risk from fire to residents and employees and to implement appropriate fire precautions to prevent fires and mitigate the risk that, should a fire break out, lives are not put at risk. This would include mitigating the risk of and from electrical fires.</p><p>The Government’s fire safety risk assessment guidance for residential care premises provides detailed advice on ensuring electrical equipment is safe, and is inspected regularly by a competent electrical engineer in accordance with the Electricity at Work Regulations.</p><p>It is for local fire and rescue authorities to determine whether the specific fire precautions and management and maintenance arrangements in place in any particular residential care premises are sufficient to comply with the provisions of the Order.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","27591","2016-02-26T14:08:57.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453669/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453669/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Care Homes: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of mandatory electrical safety checks in care homes.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453670","Home Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>Fire safety in care homes is the responsibility of the operator who is required under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 to assess the risk from fire to residents and employees and to implement appropriate fire precautions to prevent fires and mitigate the risk that, should a fire break out, lives are not put at risk. This would include mitigating the risk of and from electrical fires.</p><p>The Government’s fire safety risk assessment guidance for residential care premises provides detailed advice on ensuring electrical equipment is safe, and is inspected regularly by a competent electrical engineer in accordance with the Electricity at Work Regulations.</p><p>It is for local fire and rescue authorities to determine whether the specific fire precautions and management and maintenance arrangements in place in any particular residential care premises are sufficient to comply with the provisions of the Order.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","27590","2016-02-26T14:08:57.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453670/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453670/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Care Homes: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment her Department has undertaken of the electrical safety and adequacy of measures to prevent electrical fires in care homes in England.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27591"
