"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453672","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-26","<p>My Department will continue carrying out its responsibilities as Managing Authority of the England European Regional Development Fund programmes.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-26T14:15:19.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453672/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453672/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","European Regional Development Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what work his Department is doing in relation to its responsibility for the European Regional Development Fund.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","27684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453673","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>I refer the rt. hon. Member to the answer I gave on the EU Solidarity Fund on 25 February 2016, <em>Official Report</em>, column 455.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-29T17:29:15.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453673/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453673/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25978, whether the timetable for making a decision on applying to the EU Solidarity Fund has been extended.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","27613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453674","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-25","<p>My Department has not carried out a recent estimate of the effect of the European Regional Development Fund on economic growth.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-25T15:43:53.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453674/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453674/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","European Regional Development Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent estimate he has made of the effect of the European Regional Development Fund on economic growth.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","27659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453675","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>No.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-03-14T16:26:31.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453675/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453675/answer","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453675/answer/previousversion/47332","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453675/answer/previousversion/47332",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","European Regional Development Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of exit from the EU on his Department's work on the European Regional Development Fund.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","27660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453676","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Department has been notified of Article 4 directions for basement developments made by the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea and the City of Westminster.</p><p>The Secretary of State has modified Article 4 directions which remove office to residential permitted development rights for:</p><p>- the London Borough of Richmond; the London Borough of Sutton; Brighton and Hove City Council and Oxford City Council: to exclude those properties which had secured prior approval for the change of use from office to residential before the date the Article 4 directions took effect;</p><p>- London Borough of Camden: to reduce the geographical coverage of the Article 4 direction;</p><p>- Broxbourne Borough Council; the London Borough of Islington and the London Borough of Merton: to exclude those properties which had secured prior approval for the change of use from office to residential before the date the Article 4 directions took effect and to reduce the geographical coverage of the Article 4 directions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-01T17:07:06.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453676/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453676/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","Building Alterations: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 26570, on planning permission, which local authority made each of those article 4 directions; and what modifications his Department made to eight of those directions.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453677","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-25","<p>5 December 2015.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-25T15:44:44.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453677/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453677/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 27055, what the Government considers to be the date of first damage by floods in Cumbria during December 2015.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","27822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453678","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-01","<p>By the end of this Parliament, local authorities will fund local services from their local taxes, including £26 billion raised from business rates.</p><p>We have announced that we will conduct a review of what the needs assessment formula should be in a world in which all local government spending is funded by local resources not central grant, and use it to determine the transition to 100% business rates retention. We will develop this approach in partnership with local government.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-01T17:07:57.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453678/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453678/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will bring forward proposals to review the needs-based formula for local government.","true","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","27716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453679","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government published its response to the consultation on 9 February.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:03:32.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453679/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453679/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-22","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish as soon as possible a full analysis of responses to his Department's recent consultation on the deregulation of Sunday trading.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","27699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453680","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-29","<p>While ticket prices are matter for individual clubs, this Government is aware how important this is to so many football fans. Football is enjoying an enormous amount of financial success at present, however it should not be forgotten that this is built on the hard work and the money of millions of loyal supporters. Clubs should ensure that ticket pricing strikes the right balance between value for supporters, and generating the income necessary to sustain their business.</p><p> </p><p>I will be looking for football to embrace fully a key recommendation from a recently published Government Expert Working Group on supporter ownership and engagement that requires clubs meet with fans at least twice yearly to discuss matters of most importance.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","27674","2016-02-29T15:21:13.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453680/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453680/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Football: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent representations he has made to Premier League football clubs on the level of ticket prices.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","27783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453681","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>BT and other suppliers with funding from BDUK are obliged to provide wholesale access to all new ducts and poles built using public subsidy, in line with the requirements of the BDUK European State aid approval.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom has not conducted an assessment of the proportion of ducts that were able to have fibre blown through them without further civil works in the subsequent superfast broadband rollout. Ofcom does not hold any other information on the proportion of BT's ducts that were able to have fibre blown through them without further civil works.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T10:26:22.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453681/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453681/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he or Ofcom have made an assessment or hold information on the proportion of BT's ducts that were able to have fibre blown through them without further civil works in the superfast broadband rollout.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","27735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453682","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>As the Prime Minister said in his statement to the House on Monday, the Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T10:27:35.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453682/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453682/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Culture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if his Department will make an assessment of the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on cultural, sporting and media initiatives within the UK currently supported by the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453683","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>Ministers meet with a range of EU counterparts in the course of normal business. The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T10:28:13.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453683/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453683/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Culture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in other EU member states on the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on cultural, sporting and media initiatives currently supported by the EU within the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453684","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-25","<p>In partnership with the Football Association and the Premier League, the government is continuing to invest significant sums in grassroots football facilities every year. In addition to the £10million we give to the Football Foundation each year, this Government has dedicated £8million per year to the new 'Parklife' project that will double the number of 3G pitches and enable over 3,500 community sports matches to be played per week.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-02-25T12:17:47.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453684/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453684/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Football: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to improve access to all-weather football pitches at grassroots level.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Mr David Crausby","27690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453685","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>It is a matter for Ofcom as the independent regulator to consider whether the benefits of conducting and publishing such an assessment are proportionate to the costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On 25 February Ofcom published the initial conclusions of its Strategic Review of Digital Communications, including its strategy to promote large-scale roll-out of new ultrafast broadband networks.</p><p> </p><p>As part of that, Ofcom has said it will ask Openreach to provide a new database showing the physical location and characteristics of all of its ducts and poles, and to provide greatly improved systems and processes for access to them. This will allow competing operators to invest, plan and lay advanced networks. Ofcom will be working closely with industry to drive this forward over the coming months.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T10:29:28.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453685/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453685/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26900, if he will request that Ofcom publish an assessment of the extent to which the indicative assessment of BT's ducts in the report, Telecoms infrastructure access - sample survey of duct access, published in March 2009, was borne out in the subsequent rollout by BT of superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","27827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453686","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government published the Evaluation of Gaming Machine (Circumstances of Use) (Amendment) Regulations 2015 on 21 January. The Evaluation can be found at:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-gaming-machine-circumstances-of-useamendment-regulations-2015</p><p> </p><p>The Gambling Commission’s Licence Conditions and Codes of Practice (LCCP), include clear requirements regarding staff interaction whenever players show signs of problem gambling. The Government is clear that we expect the industry to help people stay in control of their gambling, and ensure they know where to get help and advice if they need it.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-02-29T15:18:48.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453686/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453686/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Gaming Machine Regulations 2015 on the volume of bets being staked at just under £50; and what steps his Department is taking to assess the levels of staff interaction with fixed odds betting terminal players in bookmakers.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453687","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>Ofcom regularly publishes data on premises able to receive Next Generation Access broadband services and able to receive superfast broadband services (measured at 30+Mbit/s). Their most recent data, collected in May 2015, showed that AL:UK Next Generation Access (NGA) coverage of 90% and superfast coverage of 83%; that West Midlands region NGA coverage of 91% and superfast coverage of 86%; and Coventry NGA coverage of 91% and superfast coverage of 89%.</p><p><br> The roll-out continues and the subsequent rise in superfast coverage will be reported by Ofcom in the next update later in 2016</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T16:22:28.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453687/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453687/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of homes receiving fibre-optic broadband services in (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) the UK in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","27652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453688","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Government's Superfast Broadband programme delivers superfast broadband - which delivers speeds of at least 24Mbps. Superfast broadband is available to nearly 90 per cent of homes and businesses in the UK, and we are on track to reach 95% by the end of 2017, as set out in our manifesto.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-25T11:50:52.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453688/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453688/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of fibre-optic broadband coverage across the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","27653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453689","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-25","<p>I hold regular discussions with internet service providers on a wide range of issues. A number of communications infrastructure suppliers and service providers attended the recent not-spot summit on 3 February where they were given the opportunity to discuss the challenges for both mobile and superfast broadband coverage.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-25T17:20:05.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453689/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453689/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent representations his Department has received from internet service providers on the rollout of fibre-optic broadband; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","27655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453690","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>DCMS publishes official statistics on the Broadband Performance Indicator at<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/broadband-performance-indicators" target="_blank"> https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/broadband-performance-indicators</a> with the latest numbers showing that BDUK grants to local authorities and budget transfers to devolved administrations amounted cumulatively to £406,918,848 to December 2015.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T10:23:42.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453690/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453690/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of spending on infrastructure to support fibre-optic broadband installation in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","27654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453691","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-29","<p>One of the three key licensing objectives set out in the Gambling Act 2005 is that vulnerable people should be protected from harm. All betting shop operators are required by the Gambling Commission’s Licence Conditions and Code of Practice (LCCP) to have policies and processes in place to meet this objective. In addition, the industry trade body, the Association of British Bookmakers (ABB), has a mandatory code of conduct which places additional social responsibility requirements on all of its members.</p><p> </p><p>The rate of problem gambling is at 0.6% of the adult population, which is lower than comparable jurisdictions (USA, South Africa or Australia). However we recognise that rates are significantly higher among some sections of the population, such as young men, and that gambling-related harm is a real and significant problem. The majority of current provision for treatment of problem gamblers is through the Responsible Gambling Trust’s funding of organisations such as GamCare, who provide a helpline and counselling services, and the Gordon Moody Association, which provides specialist residential treatment. Local treatment can be found through GPs and NHS addiction clinics, there is also a specialist NHS service treating gambling disorder, based in London.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that people are protected from being harmed or exploited by gambling. The Minister for Sport and Tourism has explained to the gambling industry that they are expected to demonstrate that they are improving existing player protection initiatives and evaluating the effects of previous initiatives. As the Minister said at the recent RGT harm minimisation conference, government and industry should never feel that there is an end point to social responsibility.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","27666","2016-02-29T14:32:06.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453691/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453691/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-22","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what duties apply to betting companies to ensure that vulnerable customers using their services gamble responsibly.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","27665"
